04644nam a22007095i 9780801470479DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984687358  a97808014704797 a10.7591/97808014704792doi  a(DE-B1597)481694  a(OCoLC)880579894  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0280002bisacsh04a974/.004970922231 aFisher, Julie A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNinigret, Sachem of the Niantics and Narragansetts :bDiplomacy, War, and the Balance of Power in Seventeenth-Century New England and Indian Country /cJulie A. Fisher, David J. Silverman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b2 maps, 7 line figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Picturing Ninigret -- tA Chronology of Key Events in the Life of Ninigret -- t1. Being and Becoming a Sachem -- t2. “To obtaine it by force” -- t3. “I doe but Right my owne quarrell” -- t4. A Time of Decision -- t5. Ninigret’s Narragansett War -- tEpilogue: The Small Matter of Eltwood Pomeroy’s Mare -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Key People and Places -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNinigret (c. 1600–1676) was a sachem of the Niantic and Narragansett Indians of what is now Rhode Island from the mid-1630s through the mid-1670s. For Ninigret and his contemporaries, Indian Country and New England were multipolar political worlds shaped by ever-shifting intertribal rivalries. In the first biography of Ninigret, Julie A. Fisher and David J. Silverman assert that he was the most influential Indian leader of his era in southern New England. As such, he was a key to the balance of power in both Indian-colonial and intertribal relations.Ninigret was at the center of almost every major development involving southern New England Indians between the Pe" War of 1636–37 and King Philip's War of 1675–76. He led the Narragansetts' campaign to become the region's major power, including a decades-long war against the Mohegans led by Uncas, Ninigret's archrival. To offset growing English power, Ninigret formed long-distance alliances with the powerful Mohawks of the Iroquois League and the Pocumtucks of the Connecticut River Valley. Over the course of Ninigret's life, English officials repeatedly charged him with plotting to organize a coalition of tribes and even the Dutch to roll back English settlement. Ironically, though, he refused to take up arms against the English in King Philip’s War. Ninigret died at the end of the war, having guided his people through one of the most tumultuous chapters of the colonial era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNarragansett IndiansxPolitics and governmenty17th century. 0aNiantic IndiansxKings and rulersvBiography. 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aNative American Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh1 aSilverman, David J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147047940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470479/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK